Overview¶

Credit card fraud detection has become one of the most important aspects in this era of digital payment as we move towards a cashless society. Fraudsters have developed new and ingenious tactics to gain access to credit cardholders' financial information over time.Therefore, online consumers have been facing various credit card fraudulent activities since the introduction of credit card transactions. It is important that credit card companies are able to recognize fraudulent credit card transactions so that customers are not charged for items that they did not purchase.

As an undergraduate who has profound interest in Cybersecurity, I am an enthusiast to work on the ongoing issue (i.e credit card fraud) in cyber market, hence I decided to build a credit card fraud detection algorithm.

Stay tuned !!

The Dataset¶

The following dataset has been collected and analysed during a research collaboration of Worldline and the Machine Learning Group of ULB (Universit Libre de Bruxelles) on big data mining and fraud detection. The credit card transaction dataset that is being used contains Anonymized credit card transactions labeled as Fradulent(1) or Genuine(0) made by credit cards in September 2013 by European cardholders.

We obtained this dataset from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mlg-ulb/creditcardfraud

Points to be noted:¶

The dataset contains only numerical values which are the result of Principal Component Analysis(PCA) transformation as described in the website. The reason for performing a PCA transformation was that information about credit cards is confidential and therefore, the authors who created the dataset decided to transform the orginal features into PCA components such as V1, V2, V3 ... V28.

The percentage of Fradulent Transactions was just 0.17% which makes this dataset highly imbalance, and this is an important aspect we have to take into account when pre-processing the data

Dealing with Imbalance¶

  • Why bother dealing with imbalance? An important thing to understand is that our fradulent transactions are a very small fraction of the entire data, hence when we train our models, there is a strong possibility that it can lead to overfitting. After scanning through this article (https://www.analyticsvidhya.com/blog/2020/07/10-techniques-to-deal-with-class-imbalance-in-machine-learning) , here is how I decided to tackle the issue of imbalance:
  • Random Under-Sampling: it is defined as removing some observations of the majority class(here, Non-Fradulent).In short, we will take equal number of rows for both the categories.
  • From the initial calculations, the number of fradulent transaction were 492, so we can go ahead and randomly select 492 Non-Fradulent transaction rows.
  • Now, we have equally balanced dataset of 492 rows of both Fradulent and Non-Fradulent transactions

Hypothesis Testing¶

  • Goal: check what type of classifier will be effective in detecting the fradulent transactions
  • We will be using 3 different types of classifiers: Logistic Regression, K-Neighbors Classifier, Decision Tree Classifier
  • When we train our models, we will train it on both the balanced dataset and imbalanced dataset in order to see how biased, if any, the results would be. However, we will mainly focus on hypothesis testing and it's results on the orignal data.

Cross Validation and Hyperparameter Tuning¶

  • We will train our model using a method knows as k-fold Cross Validation. Cross Validation makes sure that the model picks up general patterns of data and does not end selecting noise or irrelevant patterns from the data. In this method, the dataset is partitioned into k-folds, where we specify 'k'. The first 'k-1' folds are used in training the data and the kth fold is used in testing data. Learn more about Cross Validation here(https://towardsdatascience.com/cross-validation-in-machine-learning-72924a69872f)
  • Hyperparameter tuning is choosing a set of optimal hyperparameters for a learning algorithm. It served as a model argument whose values are set before we begin our model training. Hyperparameter is a vital step in machine learning algorithms.
  • In short, hyper-parameter tuning is just an additional optimization step on top of the Machine Learning model the find the best set of hyper-parameters that could lead us the best prediction rates and lowest error. There are numerous Hyperparameter tuning method such as Random Search, Grid Search, Bayesian Optimization. etc but we will use Grid Search CV method.
  • Grid Search: It is deemed as the simplest yet powerful method for hyperparameter tuning. The way it works is it divides the set of input hyperparameters into a grid. Then, every combination of values of this grid is tried, calculating some performance metrics using cross-validation. The point of the grid that maximizes the average value in cross-validation, is the optimal combination of values for the hyperparameters (Source: https://www.yourdatateacher.com/2021/05/19/hyperparameter-tuning-grid-search-and-random-search/#:~:text=Grid%20search%20is%20the%20simplest,performance%20metrics%20using%20cross%2Dvalidation.)

To understand more about Grid Search CV and how it works with each classifier, these links were quite helpful for me:

  1. https://www.kaggle.com/code/enespolat/grid-search-with-logistic-regression/notebook
  2. https://towardsdatascience.com/tuning-the-hyperparameters-of-your-machine-learning-model-using-gridsearchcv-7fc2bb76ff27
  3. https://machinelearningmastery.com/hyperparameter-optimization-with-random-search-and-grid-search/

The classification report prints four metrics: the precision, recall, F1, and support scores:

  • Precision: Precision basically defines the total number of correct predictions(in percent) for each cateogory(0 or 1). According to this(https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/accuracy-vs-f1-score-6258237beca2) article, when the data is imbalanced, it's not a good choice to use accuracy as an evaluation metric, instead the best ones to check the performance of model are: F1 score and confusion matrix.
  • Recall: Recall is the ability of a classifier to find all positive instances for each class i.e what percent of total positive instances did we predict.
  • F1-score: The F1 score is a weighted harmonic mean of precision and recall such that the best score is 1.0 and the worst is 0.0. As a rule of thumb, the weighted average of F1 should be used to compare classifier models, not accuracy. The best performance so far is that of k-Neighbours classifier with a score of 84%.
  • Support: Support is just the number of test samples available for testing.

Let's focus more on F1 score and Confusion Matrix. A confusion matrix is a visualization of a classification model that shows how well the model has predicted the outcomes when compared to the original ones. Usually, the predicted outcomes are stored in a variable that is then converted into a correlation table. Using the correlation table, the confusion matrix is plotted in the form of a heatmap(Source: https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/what-is-a-confusion-matrix-d1c0f8feda5).

Communication of Insights¶

Let us begin by pitching down the results obtained in Hypothesis Testing. To begin with, let's take a quick glance on accuracy scores on the balanced data: the Linear Regression classifier reported 92%, the k-Neighbors classifier reported 93%, the Decision Tree classifier 85% accuracy on testing data. Although all of these accuracy are quite high and we can certainly be happy about these results, we need to remind ourselves that we used a method called Random-Undersampling. We ended up choosing only 492 rows out of the Non-Fradulent transaction so that we match with the count of Fradulent transaction, so there's a high risk of losing out important information. Every single information in a dataset such as Credit Card matters, so even though we got a high accuracy we cannot rely on the balanced dataset models because we took a fraction of the dataset to train the models. Instead, we will focus more the entire dataset.

Speaking of the entire dataset, the F1-scores of all models are reported as follows:

  • k-Neighbors Classifier = 84.3%
  • Decision Tree Classifer = 79%
  • Logistic Regression Classifier = 69%

Looks like the k-Neighbors Classifier grabbed the first position, so let's analyze the confusion matrix in detail for this classifier. (Remember: the confusion matrix deals with testing set). The first row represents all the Non-Fraudulent transactions(0s) and we can observe that the Top-Left cell (True Negative) reports 56860 and the Top-Right cell(False Positive) reports 4 - basically, out of 56864 Non-Fraudulent transactions of the testing set, our model predicted 56860 correctly predicted those as 0(Non-Fraudulent) which is a really good prediction. We can safely state that our model did a great job in identifying what transactions were Non-Fraudulent transactions. The second row represents all the Fraudulent transactions(1s). There were a total of 98(30+68) Fraudulent transactions in the testing set and the model correctly identified 68 transactions as Fradulent. The incorrectly predicted values(30) can be inferred as error in the model.

Final Thoughts¶

We have come a long in terms of analyzing the data, identifying patterns in the various features, cleaning up the data, and successfully building 3 different classifiers on our dataset and the k-Neighbors classifier stands out in terms of accurately classifying Fraudulent and Non-Fraudulent transactions. Great job!!!

A common thought that comes across our mind is: can we deploy this model in real life? The answer is yes and no. First off, it is important to note that we are still not aware of what exactly those features (V1, V2, V3..) represent because they have been kept confidential by the people who developed the dataset. To deploy a model in real life, we need to have access to confidential information which is not that easily available. However, we gained an overview of Credit Card detection algorithm, how to deal with imbalance dataset, understanding accuracy reports. This tutorial serves as good starting point for me to dive more into the Cybersecurity field.
